I claim that it would be worthwhile to allow Python io objects to be wrapped into `std::ostream`s. Currently, one has to use `scoped_ostream_redirect` like so:

```c++
m.def("foo", [](pybind11::object io) {
    std::ostringstream out;

    pybind11::scoped_ostream_redirect redirect{out, file};

    // rest of code, using `out` as the std::ostream&
});
```

However, `std::ostream` [can be constructed by](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/io/basic_ostream/basic_ostream) a `std::streambuf`. `scoped_ostream_redirect` uses a `streambuf` implementation. Thus, it's possible to directly create a `std::ostream` from the object:

```c++
pybind11::detail::pythonbuf buffer{io};
std::ostream out{&buffer};
```

What I'm leading up to is this (currently doesn't work):

```c++
m.def("foo", [](std::ostream& out) {
    // using `out` as before
});
```

Which could be used in Python as if it were a regular Python io object:

```python
import io
out = io.StringIO()
m.foo(out)
print(out.getvalue())
```

